frameDefinitions: This frame contains nouns denoting Quantities of a specified Entity and their numerical Values.
An event or state (here termed an Eventuality) or time-Period is described in terms of the Degree to which its duration diverges from a standard.
An Agent decides temporarily not to perform a Desirable_action or not to interact with a Salient_entity.
The Quantity of a Collection occurring in a Place has a particular Measure, which is related to the amount generally needed.

This frame involves a static (primarily spatial) relationship between a Location and a Theme, in which the Theme is located in many or all subregions of the Location, and is thus construable as covering it.
These are words relating to filling containers and covering areas with some thing, things or substance, the Theme.
frameExamples: His heart attack was caused by a high cholesterol <t>level</t>.
After a <t>lengthy</t> discussion with the Foreign Minister, Mr. Qian Qichen, they met the Prime Minister.
I have actually <t>held off</t> on buying some movies by WB because of those damned cases.
There is evidence that volatile materials have always been <t>scarce</t> on the Moon .
Lionel Hutz <t>coated</t> the wall with paint.
listRoleDefinitions: <fen>Entity</fen> identifies the concept or substance being quantified by a <fen>Quantity</fen>.
Identifies the <fen>Quantity</fen>-denoting <t>target</t> word.
<fen>Value</fen> identifies the numerical amount of the <fen>Entity</fen>.

A situation, action or event whose duration is being described.  The Eventuality occurs as the External Argument if the adjective is used predicatively, or as the modified noun if the adjective is used attributively: <fex name='Eventuality'>The lecture</fex> was <t>short</t>. We had a <t>lengthy</t> <fex name='Eventuality'>conversation</fex>.

Sometimes these adjectives describe simply a period of time, rather than an event or state.  The Period almost invariably occurs as the modified noun with an attributive adjective: We waited for only a <t>short</t> <fex name='Period'>time</fex>. Use of the drug over a <t>lengthy</t> <fex name='Period'>period</fex> can cause memory loss.
The <fen>Agent</fen> decides not to engage in a <fen>Desirable_action</fen> for a while or not to interact with a <fen>Salient_entity</fen>.
<fen>Desirable_action</fen> identifies the event or activity in which the <fen>Agent</fen> does not engage for a while.
An entity that evokes a contextually inferrable <fen>Desirable_action</fen> that the <fen>Agent</fen> is temporarily forgoing.
This role identifies the interval of <fen>Time</fen> during which the the forgoing occurs.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where the temporary forgoing occurs.
The <fen>Collection</fen> whose <fen>Quantity</fen> is under consideration.
The feature of an <fen>Collection</fen> which is under discussion. This role is incorporated by all the lexical units in this frame.
The location in which the <fen>Collection</fen> occurs.
The <fen>Time</fen> during which the <fen>Collection</fen> is in the state of having  a particular <fen>Measure</fen> for the <fen>Quantity</fen>.

The <fen>Theme</fen> in this frame is the object which is described as standing in some spatial relation to a particular <fen>Location</fen>.  <fen>Theme</fen> typically occurs as the External Argument or, with passives, as a PP Complement headed by 'with' or 'by'.
<fen>Location</fen> is the entity or area with respect to which the <fen>Theme</fen>'s spatial arrangement is described.  This frame element generally occurs as an NP Object.
The time at which the <fen>Theme</fen> occupies the <fen>Location</fen>.
The <fen>Agent</fen> is the actor who instigates the filling.
The <fen>Theme</fen> is the physical object or substance which changes location.
The <fen>Goal</fen> is the area or container being filled. Goal is generally the NP Object in this frame.
An event which brings about the filling of the <fen>Goal</fen>.
When the filling occurs.
Where the filling takes place.
listRoleExamples: Their <fex><t>level</t></fex> of productivity decreased with each hour of overtime worked.
He wrote me a check in the amount <fex>of $500</fex>.
Instead, <fex>he</fex> held off on a public announcement of his decision for more than a year.
The board also waited <fex>with the appointment of seven members to the planning and zoning commission</fex> until a policy is set regarding requirements.
I ordered the blackberry cobbler with ice cream for dessert and held off <fex>on another pint</fex> as the rain kept coming down.

Saskatchewan teachers are not a happy lot as they had voted for a strike in June
<fex>then</fex> held off on it to give negotiations a chance during the summer.
The majority of specimens were poorly represented, as judged by the small size of mature plants, the immaturity of thalli or scarceness <fex>in occurrence</fex>.
Northern Pike are plentiful <fex>in Perrault Lake</fex>.
<fex>These days</fex> food is plentiful and easy to get and physical activity is no longer a part of daily life.
Rev. Lovejoy carefully brushed the rolls <fex>with butter</fex>.
